******
[1] Wellington, Palm Beach County
Date: Wed 27 Feb 2013
Source: The Horse [edited]
http://www.thehorse.com/articles/31434/wellington-fla-horse-tests-positive-for-ehv-1


A horse stabled in the Grand Prix Village (located outside of the Palm Beach International Equestrian Center [PBIEC] in Wellington, Florida) was tested for equine herpesvirus-1 (EHV-1); the animal tested negative for the nasal PCR (polymerase chain reaction) swab, but positive on blood test, according to a statement from show organizers Equestrian Sport Productions.

The affected horse has not shown any neurologic signs and there are no sick or horses or horses with positive EHV-1 tests on the PBIEC property, the statement relayed.

According to the statement, "The horse that was tested was never on the PBIEC property and was isolated on the private property in Grand Prix Village. However, 2 horses from that Grand Prix Village farm were moved into the Federation Equestre Internationale (FEI) stabling at PBIEC. Within FEI stabling, those 2 horses had no other horses directly next to them or behind them, and those 2 horses couldn't touch noses with other horses. The closest horses to the 2 exposed were across a 12-foot [3.7 m] aisle.

"On the evening of Tue 26 Feb 2013, the 2 horses from Grand Prix Village that were in FEI stabling were moved back to their farm in Grand Prix Village on the recommendation of the state veterinarian and that farm in Grand Prix Village is under quarantine."

The Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services has temporarily closed FEI stabling, the release said. No horses will be allowed to enter or leave until tests from the 2 horses from Grand Prix Village who were moved to the FEI stabling are returned at approximately 4:00 p.m. tomorrow [28 Feb 2013], the statement said.

EHV-1 is highly contagious among horses and camelids and is generally passed from horse to horse via aerosol transmission (when affected animals sneeze/cough) and contact with nasal secretions.

