******
[2] Ocala, Marion County
Date: Wed 27 Feb 2013
Source: Ocala.com [edited]
http://www.ocala.com/article/20130227/ARTICLES/130229704


Despite a state quarantine issued on Wednesday [27 Feb 2013] for all horses at the HITS [Horse shows In The Sun] showgrounds, the organizers of the Ocala Circuit are going on with the competition.

The quarantine was issued by the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Service Division of Horse Industry after 5 more horses, which were no longer on the grounds, tested positive for the equine herpesvirus (EHV-1).

No horses are allowed to leave Post Time Farm off US 27 near Ocala. Organizers will allow anyone who wants to compete onto the grounds, but once there, his or her horse cannot leave until the quarantine is lifted, which could take as long as 21 days.

It was not clear Wednesday [27 Feb 2013] how long the quarantine would last. About a week ago, tent No. 7 at the show grounds was quarantined after a horse housed there tested positive for EHV-1. Since then, no other horse on the grounds has tested positive.

"They said it could be a few days or up to 2 weeks," HITS spokeswoman Kristen Vale said of the quarantine.

The new cases all came from horses no longer on the show rounds, but which were housed in tent Nos. 3 and 6. The farms where the horses are currently found, including a 5th in Marion County, were all placed under quarantine.

The show is scheduled to run until 17 Mar 2013. Vale said there were approximately 1300 horses currently on the grounds and all scheduled competitions will continue.

[Byline: Carlos E Medina]

